## 1. Row selection by label vs position

The country name is in the first column (country), which makes it a natural 
candidate for df.set_index("country")


set_index() turns an existing column into the row index.

```python
df = pd.DataFrame({
    "country": ["Spain", "France", "Italy"],
    "population": [47, 67, 59]
})
```

Before:

```bash
   country  population
0    Spain          47
1   France          67
2    Italy          59
```

```python
df = df.set_index("country")
```
After:

```bash
         population
country
Spain            47
France           67
Italy            59
```

The "country" column is no longer a regular column — it's now the row label. 

This means you can do:
`df.loc["Spain"]` to  get Spain's row directly by name.

A few things to know:
By default it returns a new DataFrame (doesn't modify the original).
Use inplace=True or reassign like above.

To undo it: df.reset_index() moves the index back into a regular column.

You can also set multiple columns as index: df.set_index(["country", "year"]) creates a MultiIndex.


Alternatively you can filter with a boolean mask df[df["country"] == "Spain"].
Both produce the same result but teach different indexing approaches — label-based .loc vs boolean filtering.
  
  1. Wide-format data and the transpose problem                                                                      
   
  The CSV has years as column names (1800, 1801, … 2100). To plot year on the x-axis you need years to be the index, 
  not column headers. This forces you to confront .T (transpose) — turning one row (a country) into a Series where
  the index is years and the values are life expectancy. This is probably the deepest new concept in the exercise.


  3. From DataFrame to Series

After filtering one row you get a single-row DataFrame, not a Series. 
To plot cleanly you need to either .squeeze()
   or .iloc[0] to collapse it to a 1D Series. This is the first time the distinction between a DataFrame and a Series
   matters practically.

##  4. Line plot basics

plt.plot() or Series.plot(), adding plt.title(), plt.xlabel(), plt.ylabel() — the minimum anatomy of a
well-labelled chart. The subject explicitly requires all three.

we plot about 300 data points. We can not print all 300 labels on x-axis.

We ask to plot only 6 labels wiht set_major_locator()

```python
  ax = plt.gca()  # Get current axes
  ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(plt.MaxNLocator(nbins=6))
```
##  5. Column names as integers

  Gapminder year columns are integers (1800, not "1800"), which can surprise you when slicing or converting to float
  for the axis. Worth noting when the x-axis labels look wrong.

This instruction "data_plot = data.loc[country]" returns a pandas.series of 
301 rows when data is a DataFrame of 192 rows with 301 columns, Because 
.loc[country] selects a single row. 

When you extract one row from a DataFrame, pandas returns it as a Series where 
the former columns become the index.

So your 301 columns (likely years) become 301 entries in the Series, with each 
year as the index label and the corresponding value as the data. 
That's the expected behavior — it didn't add rows, it transposed a row into a 
Series.


if the DataFrame column names are string, the index of the pandas.series 
resulting  form .loc[country] keeps same type.
 .loc[] preserves the original dtypes — it just moves the column names into 
 the Series index without any type conversion.
You can  change the index type from string to integer with `data_plot.index = data_plot.index.astype(int)`

when index type is a number, plot() show only a subset of all labels.
